\cf1\f0\fs32 [How to Customize These Skins - Settings.txt]\cf2\f1\fs22\par
     Elementary's settings/user preferences are in the file "\b\i ...\\Skins\\Elementary\\@Resources\\Settings.txt\b0\i0 "; open this file in any text editor to change your preferences.  You can also right click and Elementary skin, and in the context menu select "Elementary > Settings.ini" to quickly open the file in Windows Notepad.\par
     The settings are given in Key=Value pairs; to change a setting, modify the portion after the "=" sign, save the file, and refresh any open Elementary skins.\par
\b font\b0  & \b  font2\b0  \par
...the primary and secondary fonts used by the skins.  You can use any installed font, just know that the positions of the skin elements are optimized for the two default fonts.  Changing fonts \i will\i0  throw off positioning and you will have to edit the skin .inis to alter that.\par
\b color\b0  \par
...the color of the skins, given in Decimal or Hexadecimal format.  The default is 255,255,255,180; for a dark skins, try 0,0,0,200 and play around with it from there.  (See the "Helpful Links and Tools" section for a link to more information on color codes in Rainmeter.)\par
\b style\b0  \par
...sets the attributes of the text in the skins.  Valid values are "NORMAL," BOLD," "ITALIC," and "BOLDITALIC."\par
\b scalar \par
\b0 ...modifies the size of the anolog clock.  Use a larger number to increase the size, or a smaller number to decrease it.  I would recommend staying between 1.5 and 5.0.\par
\b location \par
\b0 ...where you want weather information for.  This can be a US or Canadian zip code, a CITY,STATE pair, a CITY,COUNTRY pair, a 3 or 4 lettter airport code, or a latitude and longitude (LAT,LON).  What you put here must be URL friendly, so either leave out/replace the spaces, or encode your location and use the encoded value (i.e. "New York, New York" becomes "New%20York%2C%20New%20York").\par
\b language\b0  \par
...the two letter ISO 639-1 code for your preferred language.  Languages currently included are: \par
